column3: Great job passing all the autotests!
Nice use of in-line comments!
In-line comments are required for more complex code.
Added an attribute that's not needed (like self.corpus). Why store this?
It's often best to use the getter/accessor method within the class, rather than accessing the attributes directly.
Protected attributes that start with an underscore should not be accessed from outside of the class!
Single characters are not meaningful variable names. Use more descriptive names.
Do not need to cast count to an int, as it should already be passed to the method as an integer (see docstring).
The suggested str.startswith(..) method is significantly more efficient than 'in', and also more accurate - only want to check the beginning!
Fails the autotest here because you need to check length is the same, or else they don't match!
Matching could be simplified: Single loop where you check if 2 characters are equal, or if pattern is a wildcard character.
using the str.format(..) method could also work nicely here, instead of concatenation!
Count should be cast to an int before being passed to FreqWord initializer.
It's better to exit the 'with open() as' block as soon as you're done with the file, meaning it's slightly preferred to have the return statement outside of the 'with' block.
Matching could be simplified: Single loop

column1: where you use matches_pattern if '.' in criteria, and has_prefix otherwise.

column3: Don't need to check that length of new_list > 3 in order to slice!
A list comprehension could make the converting to a string version a little more succinct.
Using '\n'.join(lst) could be more succinct for combining the list of strings into a single string and would also avoid the extra newline at the end that is causing a failed autotest.
Nice use of list comprehension!
Using '|'.join([]) string method would  avoid the error that shows in TestResults.txt, so you wouldn't have to handle a word without results specially.
Nice use of str.join! A list comprehension could make converting the items to a list of str more succinct.
